    "long_instructions": "Before we start writing more code, let's make sure your program has a **comment** -- a note written for humans to read, not the computer.\r\n\r\n## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Add a **comment** at the top of the code that says what the program does.\r\n\r\n   **Hint:** Start the line with `#`. For example:\r\n   \r\n   ```\r\n   # This is a comment\r\n   print(\"Hello!\")\r\n   ```\r\n\r\n2. You can describe what the code does now or what you plan to make it say.\r\n\r\n3. Then run the program again and make sure your message still prints!\r\n\r\n   <i class=\"fa-solid fa-hand-back-point-right\"></i> **By the way!** Click the book icon above the workspace anytime you want to reference Python documentation.\r\n   \r\n   ![python documentation book icon](https://images.code.org/901506f120f08a705ac5c65077f31e2b-image-1746033222447.12.23 AM.png)\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nPython ignores anything that comes after a `#`.\r\n\r\nComments are a great way to explain your code -- to yourself and others!",
